        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18700",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This is not an issue...\n\nAPI for isDate() says:\n{code}\n     * Checks if the given date is a real date or datepart.\n     * Returns false if a expected datepart is missing or a datepart exceeds its possible border.\n     * But the check will only be done for the expected dateparts which are given by format.\n     * If no format is given the standard dateformat for the actual locale is used.\n     * f.e. 30.February.2007 will return false if format is 'dd.MMMM.YYYY'\n{code}\n\nYou did not define a format in your example so the standard format from your locale is used.\nThis means the used format differs on the browser or environment settings.\n\nAnd the input you gave follows no known default format in any locale so the returned \"false\" is correct.\n\nAs wether the class nor the function has been changed in past (since 1.0.2) it must be related to different browser or server settings.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T11:52:38.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T11:52:38.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18704",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks Thomas for your explanation.\n\nAt this point I'm going to ask you an additional information.\nWhat about if I don't know input date format and I just want to validate input? \n\nFor example, strtotime() is able to accept whatever kind of input that can be mapped as a datetime.\nIs there any way to achieve this with Zend_Date?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T15:09:16.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T15:09:16.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18705",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks Thomas for your explanation.\n\nAt this point I'm going to ask you an additional information.\nWhat about if I don't know input date format and I just want to validate input? \n\nFor example, strtotime() is able to accept whatever kind of input that can be mapped as a datetime.\nIs there any way to achieve this with Zend_Date?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T15:09:21.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T15:09:21.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18706",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Sorry for the double comment, network problem! :|\nIf you need more details, please have a look at the latest two comments for ZF-2524",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T15:10:08.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T15:10:08.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18707",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Tonight my brain is definitely unlinked!\nThis is the right issue id: ZF-2334",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T15:11:25.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T15:11:25.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18716",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Then you really have a problem...\n\nBecause a date in RSS Format is not valid if you need ISO... and an ISO date on the other hand is not valid if you expect ATOM date...\n\nYou see where the problem is ?\nYou can't say all dates are valid, because this is not true...\n\nEven dates like \"1234-99-55 354:99:99\" could be seen as valid in some environments but most people will say that's no date.\n\nIf you do not know how the date is formatted then Zend_Date is not the right class for you.\nYou can use Zend_Date_Format and parse the date with it.. but then you will have to decide yourself if the returned date parts are an valid date in your eyes or not.\n\nAnd related to strtotime... this is the same thing what Zend_Date also does on initiation...\nYou said yourself that you can initiate Zend_Date and the date is accepted like use it with strtotime.\nBut strtotime does not validate the input like Zend_Date::isValid(), it generates a timestamp from the date, exactly like Zend_Date.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T15:35:24.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T15:35:24.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18719",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks for your answer, Thomas.\nI'm Sorry, I have one more question.\n\nI had a more deep look at Zend_Date and Zend_Locale and I made a few tests.\nI basically changed the following line in Zend_Locale\n\n{code}private static $_Default = \"en\";{code}\n\nto\n\n{code}private static $_Default;{code}\n\nas it was when I first tested the class after your default locale fix, and it did the trick!\nI can use Zend_Date::isDate() to validate against any format... or at least it seems to work. All my tests passed.\n\nI can't understand why you decided to change $_Default default value in a second time, in r7357.\nI do apologize if you find this question too idiot. I don't have high level \"locale\" skills. :|",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=weppos",
                        "name": "weppos",
                        "displayName": "Simone Carletti",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-30T16:13:40.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-30T16:13:40.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/18731",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Many environments seem not to have a locale set.\n\nThis makes problems when using classes where the locale is detected automatically. In such cases an exception was raised in past, saying that the locale can not be detected.\n\nThis made users angry because they were not able to fetch this exception. Don't ask me why...\nSo we decided to add a default locale 'en' as fallback so that no exception is raised anymore in such environments.\n\nSo the question is what $format and $locale is before line 4625 in both cases... this is the real difference. And the question why the locale of your environment can not be detected.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-01-31T01:32:55.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-01-31T01:32:55.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
